        "committer": {
          "name": "Hiroshi Nishida",
          "email": "hnishida@thelustrecollective.com",
          "date": "2026-04-15 22:21:20.000000000",
          "tz": -420
        },
        "subject": "LU-20119 selinux: introduce lustre_helper_t domain",
        "message": "LU-20119 selinux: introduce lustre_helper_t domain\n\nReplace the kernel_generic_helper_t-based rules with a dedicated\nlustre_helper_t domain and lustre_helper_exec_t file type.\n\nkernel_generic_helper_t is a shared type assigned by the kernel to\nevery process spawned via call_usermodehelper(), regardless of which\nsubsystem initiated the call. Granting permissions to it affects\nall UMH callers, not just Lustre.\n\nThe new approach labels the Lustre helper binaries (l_getsepol,\nlctl, l_getidentity, l_getauth) as lustre_helper_exec_t via the\nnew lustre_helpers.fc file context spec, and adds a type_transition\nrule so that kernel_t transitions to lustre_helper_t on exec of\nthose binaries. All Lustre-specific permissions are confined to\nlustre_helper_t.\n\nOn RHEL/Rocky 9 the base policy's kernel_t -> kernel_generic_helper_t\ntransition covers all UMH helpers and Lustre works without this\nmodule. On RHEL/Rocky 10 that transition was removed together with\nkernel_generic_helper_t itself, so kernel_t execs the helper binary\ndirectly; the kernel_t -> lustre_helper_t transition handles that.\n\nMakefile.am is updated to pass -f lustre_helpers.fc to\nsemodule_package and to run restorecon after module installation.\n\nTested on Rocky 10.1 (selinux-policy-42.1.7) with SELinux enforcing.\n\nChange-Id: Ie63b64e4b90125e003934c2b133e113b0ed52b5c\nSigned-off-by: Hiroshi Nishida <hnishida@thelustrecollective.com>\n"
      },
      "branch": "refs/heads/master"
    }
  },
